				<h1>Entry and exit</h1>
				<h2>Passport validity</h2>
				<p>Your passport must be valid up to the end of your stay in Portugal.</p>
				<h2>Visa</h2>
				<p>You can stay as a tourist for up to 3 months.</p>
				<p>After 3 months, you must apply for a Registration Certificate from the local Camara Municipal (Town Hall).</p>
				<h2>UK Emergency Travel Document</h2>
				<p>You can use an Emergency Travel Document (ETD) to enter and leave Portugal.</p>
			</section>

			<section class="part" id="safety-and-security">
				<h1>Safety and security</h1>
				<p>Most visits to Portugal are trouble-free. Take normal safety precautions.</p>
				<h2>Road travel</h2>
				<p>See <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaa.com%2Fmotoring_advice%2Ftouring_tips%2Fportugal.pdf&sa=D&sntz=1&usg=AFQjCNGAd5mKjShGtBjTo-76OvTC9E9L6A">AA</a> and <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.rac.co.uk%2Ftravel%2Fdriving-abroad%2Fcountries%2Fportugal%2F&sa=D&sntz=1&usg=AFQjCNHxo73L4gFbUbr0rDxhpGyLEi4P9g">RAC</a> guides to driving in Portugal.</p>
			</section>

			<section class="part" id="local-laws">
				<h1>Local laws</h1>
				<h2>ID</h2>
				<p>You must show ID if asked by the police or other authority. A photocopy of your passport is usually acceptable.</p>
				<h2>Gambling</h2>
				<p>Gambling is legal only in licensed places, like official casinos.</p>
				<p>Even games like bingo are illegal on unlicensed premises.</p>
				<p>The police act on reports of illegal gambling without warning. Anyone present can be arrested, charged, fined or imprisoned.</p>
				<p>If you’re unsure, check the place you’re entering is licensed.</p>
				<p>Find guidance on gambling at the <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.turismodeportugal.pt%2FPortugu%25C3%25AAs%2FAreasAtividade%2FInspecaoJogos%2Fjogoilicito%2FDocuments%2FGambling%2520in%2520Portugal%2520-%2520Information%2520Leaflet.pdf&sa=D&sntz=1&usg=AFQjCNFCLBXYYm9pMCd-pJPb6EN7FiSemQ">Portuguese Tourist Authority website</a>.</p>
			</section>

			<section class="part" id="health">
				<h1>Health</h1>
				<p>For health advice on Egypt, visit the National Travel Health Network and Centre.</p>
				<p>Medical facilities outside Cairo, major cities and resorts can be basic.  In an emergency, seek treatment in Cairo or the nearest big city or town.
				In an emergency dial 123 and ask for an ambulance.
				Pre-travel Hepatitis A vaccine is now recommended for all travellers.
				Information about healthcare abroad, including a country-by-country guide to reciprocal healthcare agreements with the UK, is available from <a href="http://www.nhs.uk">NHS Choices</a>.</p>
			</section>

			<section class="part" id="where-to-get-help">
				<h1>Where to get help</h1>
				<p>If you have any questions about travelling, email the <a href="TravelAdvicePublicEnquiries@fco.gov.uk">FCO Travel Advice Team</a>. To find out if your passport is valid for travel to this country, see <a href="/travel-advice/egypt/entry-and-exit">Entry and Exit</a>.</p>
				<h2>Emergencies</h2>
				<p>Call 123 when in Egypt.</p>
				<h2>Embassies</h2>
				<p>[served by API]</p>
				<h2>Arrested abroad</h2>
				<p>Find out what help you can get if you or someone you know is <a href="/help-if-you-are-arrested-abroad">arrested abroad</a>.</p>
				<h2>UK Emergency Travel Document</h2>
				<p>You can use an Emergency Travel Document (ETD) to leave Egypt. But you can’t use one to enter the country.</p>
